 ---
 Phased Implementation

 Phase 0: Foundation (Days 1-2)

 - Init git, .gitignore, pyproject.toml with uv
 - alice/config.py — Pydantic Settings (adapt from my_ai)
 - alice/persona.yaml — Alice personality def
 - .env.example, alice/main.py stub
 - Create techstack.note, features.note

 Phase 1: Text Chat Brain (Days 3-5)

 - alice/brain/llm/base.py — abstract LLMProvider
 - alice/brain/llm/groq_provider.py — Groq streaming (adapt my_ai/ollama.py)
 - alice/brain/llm/ollama_provider.py — reuse from my_ai
 - alice/brain/llm/router.py — provider selection
 - alice/memory/store.py — SQLite sessions + messages
 - alice/brain/engine.py — main brain loop
 - Test: type in terminal → get Alice response

 Phase 2: Tool System (Days 6-9)

 - alice/tools/base.py — BaseTool w/ permission model
 - Implement tools: system_info, pc_control, file_ops, weather, news, music, apps
 - Wire tools into LLM via function calling (Groq native support)
 - Test: "Alice, open Chrome" → Chrome opens

 Phase 3: Voice Input — STT + Wake Word (Days 10-13)

 - alice/audio/listener.py — mic capture (sounddevice)
 - alice/audio/vad.py — Silero VAD
 - alice/audio/wake_word.py — Porcupine "Hey Alice"
 - alice/audio/clap_detector.py — amplitude spike detection
 - alice/brain/stt/faster_whisper.py — local STT
 - Wire: mic → wake/clap → VAD → STT → brain
 - Test: say "Hey Alice, what time is it?" → text response

 Phase 4: Voice Output — TTS (Days 14-16)

 - alice/brain/tts/edge_tts.py — Microsoft neural TTS
 - alice/brain/tts/piper_tts.py — local fallback
 - Audio playback via sounddevice
 - Interrupt handling (stop TTS when user speaks)
 - Test: full voice loop — speak → Alice speaks back

 Phase 5: Speaker Verification (Days 17-19)

 - scripts/enroll_voice.py — record 5-10 voice samples
 - alice/audio/speaker_verify.py — SpeechBrain ECAPA-TDNN
 - Cosine similarity threshold, reject unauthorized voices
 - Test: Alice responds to Chester, ignores others

 Phase 6: Tauri Desktop UI (Days 20-25)

 - Init Tauri v2 in ui/
 - alice/server.py — WebSocket bridge
 - Build UI: chat log, voice viz (canvas orb), status, settings
 - Dark glassmorphism theme (purple accent #7c3aed)
 - System tray via pystray
 - Test: proper desktop app with real-time chat

 Phase 7: Trigger Sequences (Days 26-28)

 - Double clap → parallel: play Shoot To Thrill + launch apps side-by-side + weather + news briefing
 - "Hey Alice" → launch apps + greeting
 - Global hotkey (Ctrl+Shift+A)
 - Test: double clap triggers full Iron Man experience

 Phase 8: Bilingual EN/JA (Days 29-32)

 - Language detection + manual toggle
 - Switch STT to multilingual model in JA mode
 - Edge-TTS ja-JP-NanamiNeural for Japanese
 - UI: Japanese response + English subtitle below
 - LLM provides both languages in structured output
 - Test: Alice speaks Japanese with English subtitles

 Phase 9: Memory & Learning (Days 33-37)

 - Preference tracking ("I like dark mode" → stored)
 - Usage pattern detection (common commands, time patterns)
 - Proactive suggestions ("It's 8 PM — open anime apps?")
 - /remember command
 - Dynamic context injection into LLM prompt
 - Test: Alice remembers preferences across sessions

 Phase 10: Polish (Days 38-42)

 - Error handling, graceful failures
 - Lazy-load heavy models for fast startup
 - Auto-start on Windows boot
 - Structured logging
 - Test on both laptop + desktop
 - README documentation

 ---
 Feasibility Notes

 Easy (high confidence):
 - Text chat w/ Groq/Ollama — Chester already has this in my_ai
 - Tool system — both references have clean patterns
 - STT w/ Faster-Whisper — mature, ~150MB, CPU-friendly
 - TTS w/ Edge-TTS — free, zero setup, JA support
 - PC control — standard Python subprocess/psutil
 - SQLite memory — Chester knows the pattern

 Medium (needs careful work):
 - Wake word — Porcupine free tier supports custom "Hey Alice"
 - Speaker verification — threshold tuning needs experimentation
 - Clap detection — must filter noise (typing, drops). Use: 2 peaks, 0.3-0.8s apart, min amplitude, followed by 0.5s silence
 - Window management — Win32 API for side-by-side positioning
 - Tauri on Win10 desktop — may need WebView2 manual install

 Hard (expect iteration):
 - Bilingual JA — LLM must produce both JA text + EN translation reliably
 - Natural conversation trigger ("what do you think, Alice?") — deferred to later phase, start with prefix-only
 - Proactive suggestions — UX challenge, start conservative

 ---
 Verification Plan

 Each phase has a concrete deliverable test:
 1. Terminal text chat works
 2. "Open Chrome" opens Chrome
 3. Voice input transcribes correctly
 4. Full voice loop (speak → hear Alice)
 5. Voice auth accepts Chester, rejects others
 6. Desktop app shows real-time chat
 7. Double clap triggers boot sequence
 8. Japanese mode with subtitles works
 9. Preferences persist across sessions
 10. Clean startup/shutdown on both machines

